{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567630"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19179"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19179"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.11,0.27,0.28,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11913"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113146"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11913"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19179"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95173"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"8928"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46711"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113146"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-year history of gradually worsening skin changes. She reports dark patches on her trunk and palms, and thickened, rough skin on her palms and soles. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She emigrated from Bangladesh two months ago, where she lived in a rural village for 20 years and relied on a deep tube well for drinking water.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is diffuse hyperpigmentation of the trunk and palms with a \u0027raindrop\u0027 pattern. Her palms and soles show symmetrical hyperkeratosis. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hair arsenic analysis","Skin biopsy","Serum arsenic level","24-hour urine arsenic level","Nail arsenic analysis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic cutaneous manifestations of chronic arsenic exposure, including hyperpigmentation with a characteristic raindrop pattern and palmoplantar hyperkeratosis. Her history of using deep tube well water in Bangladesh for 20 years is significant, as groundwater arsenic contamination is a major public health issue in that region. The skin changes typically develop after years of exposure and persist for months to years after exposure ceases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urine arsenic level\u003C/strong\u003E is the most reliable test for confirming arsenic exposure. While it best reflects recent exposure, it can detect arsenic and its metabolites for several months after chronic exposure has ceased, particularly in cases of long-term exposure where arsenic has accumulated in tissues. The test should specifically measure inorganic arsenic and its metabolites, as organic arsenic from seafood consumption can cause false positives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E may show characteristic histological changes but is not specific enough to confirm arsenic exposure. It would be more useful in ruling out other differential diagnoses if the clinical picture was less clear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum arsenic level\u003C/strong\u003E is less reliable than urine testing as it only reflects very recent exposure (within hours) and levels fluctuate significantly. It would not be useful in this case where exposure ceased six months ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHair arsenic analysis\u003C/strong\u003E can provide information about exposure over months but is subject to external contamination and standardisation issues. While it could potentially show historical exposure, it is more useful in forensic settings than clinical diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENail arsenic analysis\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially useful for documenting historical exposure, is also subject to external contamination and standardisation problems. It is not recommended as an initial diagnostic test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming the diagnosis, management involves ensuring no ongoing exposure, monitoring for complications (including skin cancer and other malignancies), and providing reassurance that skin changes may gradually improve over time, though some may be permanent.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic arsenic exposure commonly presents with characteristic skin changes including hyperpigmentation and hyperkeratosis.","24-hour urine arsenic level is the most reliable test for confirming arsenic exposure and can detect exposure up to several months after cessation.","Arsenic exposure can occur through contaminated drinking water, particularly from deep tube wells in certain geographical regions."],"references":["Keil DE, Berger-Ritchie J, McMillin GA. Testing for toxic elements: A focus on arsenic, cadmium, lead, and mercury. Laboratory Medicine. 2011;42(12):735-741.","Baker BA. Chronic arsenic exposure and its health implications. Toxicol Rev. 2018;37(4):470-478.","Ngan, V. Chronic arsenic poisoning. DermNet. Revised August 2021. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/chronic-arsenic-poisoning"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95173"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19179"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95173"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-09T21:05:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-09T21:05:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11913"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113146"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Arsenic exposure","synonyms":["Arsenic toxicity"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-15T11:46:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T11:46:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"contributions","id":"27917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/contributions/27917"},"attributes":{"finalizedAt":"2025-01-27T09:05:17+10:30","userDetails":{"name":"Addison Davis","title":"Dr","isExpert":true,"position":"Rural Generalist","training":"Consultant","credentials":"BBiomed, MD, FRACGP-RG, EMC, SHCP","institutionOther":"University of Tasmania"}},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11913"}},"contributionTier":{"data":{"type":"contributionTiers","id":"1"}},"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"contributionType":{"data":{"type":"contributionTypes","id":"1"}}}},{"type":"contributions","id":"30659","links":{"self"